{"title_page": "Shamim Kabir", "text_new": "{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n'''Anwarul Kabir Shamim''' (1944 \u2013 29 July 2019)<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tigercricket.com.bd/2019/07/29/condolence-anwarul-kabir-shamim-1945-2019/ |title=CONDOLENCE : Anwarul Kabir Shamim (1945-2019) |accessdate=2019-07-29}}</ref> was a [[Bangladesh]]i [[cricket]]er. He led [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]] in its first international match, against the touring [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC), in [[Dhaka]], in January 1977. The tall and lanky opener had a successful match, scoring 30 and 25. Kabir also captained the East Zone side at [[Chittagong]] and scored 29 in the second innings.\n\n==First-class career==\nKabir made his [[first-class cricket]] debut playing for [[East Pakistan first-class cricket teams|East Pakistan]] against [[List of Karachi first-class cricket teams|Karachi Greens]] in November 1961. In December 1964, he scored his maiden first-class half-century. Playing for Dacca University against a strong PIA bowling attack, at the Dacca Stadium (now known as Bangabandhu National Stadium), he scored 64 in the first innings. He was in good form that season, as in March 1965, he scored 55 against Dacca, in a match played at the Outer Stadium. His highest score of 89 came in January 1968, when he scored 89 in the first innings for East Pakistan (Green) against the East Pakistan Railways at the Dacca Stadium, sharing a 101-run third-wicket partnership with the skipper [[Abdul Latif (cricketer)|M. A. Latif]].<ref>{{cite web |title=East Pakistan Greens v East Pakistan Railways 1967-68 |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29253.html |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOverall in his 15 first-class matches Shamim scored 411 runs at an average of 17.86. He was also an occasional [[wicket-keeper]], with one stumping to his credit.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/43/43468/43468.html| title = Shamim Kabir| publisher = www.cricketarchive.com | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==After retirement==\nHe retired from international cricket after the 1976\u201377 season. [[Raquibul Hasan]] took over the captaincy from him. After his retirement from international cricket, he got heavily involved with cricket administration, and helped in the early development of cricket in [[Bangladesh]]. He managed the national team at the [[ICC Trophy]] in 1982 and 1986.<ref>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 2020, pp. 222\u201323.</ref> He played most of his club cricket in [[Dhaka]], with the Azad Boys Club.<ref>Hasan Babli. \"Antorjartik Crickete Bangladesh\".  Khelar Bhuban Prakashani, November 1994.</ref> He received the National Sports Award in 1999 for his service to Bangladesh cricket.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n== Death ==\nHe died in 2019 at the age of 74.<ref name=\"dhakatribune\">{{Cite news |url=http://archive.fo/JCIc5 |title=Bangladesh\u2019s first cricket captain Shamim Kabir dies |date=2019-07-29 |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=-\n| title=[[:Category:Bangladeshi cricket captains|Bangladeshi cricket Captains]]\n| years=1976\u20131977\n| after=[[Raquibul Hasan]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Marylebone Cricket Club cricket team in Bangladesh in 1976-77]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |last=Islam |first=K. Z. |date=13 February 2006 |title=Cricket Then And Now: Friends along the way |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/suppliments/2006/15thanniv/sports/sports12.htm |work=15th Anniversary Special |publisher=The Daily Star}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kabir, Shamim}}\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:East Pakistan cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dacca University cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dacca cricketers]]\n[[Category:East Zone (Pakistan) cricketers]]\n[[Category:People of East Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bangladeshi cricketer}}\n'''Anwarul Kabir Shamim''' (1944 \u2013 29 July 2019)<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tigercricket.com.bd/2019/07/29/condolence-anwarul-kabir-shamim-1945-2019/ |title=CONDOLENCE : Anwarul Kabir Shamim (1945-2019) |accessdate=2019-07-29}}</ref> was a [[Bangladesh]]i [[cricket]]er. He led [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]] in its first international match, against the touring [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC), in [[Dhaka]], in January 1977. The tall and lanky opener had a successful match, scoring 30 and 25. Kabir also captained the East Zone side at [[Chittagong]] and scored 29 in the second innings.\n\n==First-class career==\nKabir made his [[first-class cricket]] debut playing for [[East Pakistan cricket teams|East Pakistan]] against [[List of Karachi first-class cricket teams|Karachi Greens]] in November 1961. In December 1964, he scored his maiden first-class half-century. Playing for Dacca University against a strong PIA bowling attack, at the Dacca Stadium (now known as Bangabandhu National Stadium), he scored 64 in the first innings. He was in good form that season, as in March 1965, he scored 55 against Dacca, in a match played at the Outer Stadium. His highest score of 89 came in January 1968, when he scored 89 in the first innings for East Pakistan (Green) against the East Pakistan Railways at the Dacca Stadium, sharing a 101-run third-wicket partnership with the skipper [[Abdul Latif (cricketer)|M. A. Latif]].<ref>{{cite web |title=East Pakistan Greens v East Pakistan Railways 1967-68 |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/29/29253.html |website=CricketArchive |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOverall in his 15 first-class matches Shamim scored 411 runs at an average of 17.86. He was also an occasional [[wicket-keeper]], with one stumping to his credit.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/43/43468/43468.html| title = Shamim Kabir| publisher = www.cricketarchive.com | accessdate = 2009-09-24}}</ref>\n\n==After retirement==\nHe retired from international cricket after the 1976\u201377 season. [[Raquibul Hasan]] took over the captaincy from him. After his retirement from international cricket, he got heavily involved with cricket administration, and helped in the early development of cricket in [[Bangladesh]]. He managed the national team at the [[ICC Trophy]] in 1982 and 1986.<ref>''[[Wisden Cricketers' Almanack|Wisden]]'' 2020, pp. 222\u201323.</ref> He played most of his club cricket in [[Dhaka]], with the Azad Boys Club.<ref>Hasan Babli. \"Antorjartik Crickete Bangladesh\".  Khelar Bhuban Prakashani, November 1994.</ref> He received the National Sports Award in 1999 for his service to Bangladesh cricket.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n== Death ==\nHe died in 2019 at the age of 74.<ref name=\"dhakatribune\">{{Cite news |url=http://archive.fo/JCIc5 |title=Bangladesh\u2019s first cricket captain Shamim Kabir dies |date=2019-07-29 |access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before=-\n| title=[[:Category:Bangladeshi cricket captains|Bangladeshi cricket Captains]]\n| years=1976\u20131977\n| after=[[Raquibul Hasan]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Marylebone Cricket Club cricket team in Bangladesh in 1976-77]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |last=Islam |first=K. Z. |date=13 February 2006 |title=Cricket Then And Now: Friends along the way |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/suppliments/2006/15thanniv/sports/sports12.htm |work=15th Anniversary Special |publisher=The Daily Star}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kabir, Shamim}}\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cricketers]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:East Pakistan cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dacca University cricketers]]\n[[Category:Dacca cricketers]]\n[[Category:East Zone (Pakistan) cricketers]]\n[[Category:People of East Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "Sammyrice", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFirst-